Below are **practical, battle‑tested best practices for designing `Suspense` fallback UI**, with a strong focus on **hydration performance, UX clarity, and avoiding common mistakes**—tailored for **Next.js (App Router)**.

***

# ✅ Best Practices for `Suspense` Fallback UI

## 🧠 First principle (important)

> **A fallback is not a loading screen — it’s a *temporary stand‑in* while hydration or streaming completes.**

Good fallback UI should:

*   Reduce *perceived* wait time
*   Avoid layout shifts
*   Never block interaction

***

## ✅ 1. Match the final layout (avoid CLS)

### ❌ Bad

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
  <ClientChart />
</Suspense>
```

*   Layout jumps when chart appears
*   Causes **CLS**
*   Feels slow

***

### ✅ Good (Skeleton that matches size)

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<ChartSkeleton />}>
  <ClientChart />
</Suspense>
```

```tsx
function ChartSkeleton() {
  return <div style={{ height: 300 }} className="skeleton" />;
}
```

✅ Stable layout\
✅ Better perceived performance\
✅ No visual jank

***

## ✅ 2. Prefer skeletons over spinners

### ✅ Skeletons

*   Communicate *structure*
*   Reduce perceived waiting
*   Especially good for hydration delays

### ❌ Spinners

*   Indicate *waiting*, not progress
*   Can feel slower during hydration

📌 **Rule**

*   Above‑the‑fold → skeletons
*   Background tasks → spinners

***

## ✅ 3. Keep fallback UI non‑interactive

Hydration is incomplete inside `Suspense`.

### ❌ Bad

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<button>Click me</button>}>
  <InteractivePanel />
</Suspense>
```

*   Button doesn’t work
*   Confuses users
*   Hurts INP

***

### ✅ Good

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<DisabledButton />}>
  <InteractivePanel />
</Suspense>
```

✅ Visually clear\
✅ No fake affordances

***

## ✅ 4. Make fallback cheap to render

Fallback UI **renders immediately** — keep it lightweight.

### ❌ Avoid in fallback

*   Heavy images
*   Components with state
*   JS logic
*   Animations tied to state

### ✅ Ideal fallback

*   Static JSX
*   Minimal CSS
*   No hooks

✅ Faster paint\
✅ No extra hydration cost

***

## ✅ 5. Use different fallbacks for different layers

### ❌ One giant Suspense fallback

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<PageSkeleton />}>
  <EntirePage />
</Suspense>
```

➡️ No staging benefit\
➡️ Hydration still blocked

***

### ✅ Layered Suspense (recommended)

```tsx
<Page>
  <Header /> {/* no suspense */}

  <Suspense fallback={<ChartSkeleton />}>
    <Chart />
  </Suspense>

  <Suspense fallback={<CommentsSkeleton />}>
    <Comments />
  </Suspense>
</Page>
```

✅ Critical UI interactive first\
✅ Progressive hydration\
✅ Better INP

***

## ✅ 6. Never hide critical actions in fallback

⚠️ **Critical CTA must not wait for hydration**

### ❌ Bad

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<CTAPlaceholder />}>
  <BuyButton />
</Suspense>
```

User can’t click “Buy” quickly ❌

***

### ✅ Good

```tsx
<BuyButton />              {/* hydrates early */}
<Suspense fallback={<ExtrasSkeleton />}>
  <Recommendations />
</Suspense>
```

✅ Business‑critical UI first

***

## ✅ 7. Use intentional visual affordances

Fallback should **signal loading clearly**, not look broken.

✅ Recommended:

*   Shimmer skeletons
*   Subtle opacity
*   Placeholder text like “Loading…”

❌ Avoid:

*   Empty white space
*   Broken images
*   Abrupt content changes

***

## ✅ 8. Avoid nesting too deeply

### ❌ Over‑nested Suspense

```tsx
<Suspense>
  <A>
    <Suspense>
      <B />
    </Suspense>
  </A>
</Suspense>
```

➡️ Hard to reason about\
➡️ Confusing hydration flow

***

### ✅ Practical rule

*   1–2 Suspense layers per page
*   Based on UX, not component structure

***

## ✅ 9. Make fallback accessible

Fallback UI **must still be accessible**.

✅ Do this:

*   ARIA roles for skeletons if needed
*   Don’t trap focus
*   Avoid auto‑announcing spinners



***

## ✅ 10. Test fallback under slow conditions

### ✅ Always test with:

*   Slow 3G (Chrome DevTools)
*   CPU throttling
*   Low‑end Android emulation

Ask:

*   Can I click primary actions quickly?
*   Does layout jump?
*   Does fallback feel intentional?

***

## ✅ Recommended fallback checklist ✅

Before shipping a fallback, confirm:

✔ Matches final layout\
✔ No interaction required\
✔ Cheap to render\
✔ No layout shift\
✔ Clear loading signal\
✔ Doesn’t block critical UX

***

## 🧠 Common anti‑patterns (avoid these)

| Anti‑pattern         | Why bad          |
| -------------------- | ---------------- |
| Spinner everywhere   | Feels slow       |
| Interactive fallback | Broken UX        |
| Global Suspense      | Blocks hydration |
| Empty placeholders   | Confusing        |
| Heavy animations     | Adds cost        |

***

## ✅ Example: Production‑grade Suspense usage

```tsx
export default function Page() {
  return (
    <>
      <Hero /> {/* server, instant */}

      <Suspense fallback={<ChartSkeleton />}>
        <ClientChart />
      </Suspense>

      <Suspense fallback={<ReviewsSkeleton />}>
        <Reviews />
      </Suspense>
    </>
  );
}
```

✅ Fast first interaction\
✅ Progressive hydration\
✅ Clear visual feedback

***

## 🏁 Final takeaway (one‑liner)

> **A good Suspense fallback preserves layout, costs almost nothing, and lets users interact with what matters while hydration finishes.**

